- In C, 2D arrays are stored in row-major order, where each row’s elements are stored consecutively in memory. This makes row-wise access efficient.

- Column-wise access (column-major traversal) is possible but less efficient since columns aren’t stored contiguously. Knowing these traversal methods is key for optimizing programs and interfacing with systems that use column-major storage, such as Fortran.

